  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Girls# Right to Education in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Great Idea Phase IIII

Considering the learning and successes of the phases of the pilot project implemented in Parwan province - and following MOE mandate which is education for all in order to enable all students to benefit from high quality teaching, CHA in close cooperation with its partners, intends to implement the 4th phase of project GREAT IDEA. The target area for this intervention will be 59 schools in which 21 previous and 38 new schools in four remote districts of the provinces including parwan, panjsher, Kapisa and Kabul. Besides, CHA would consider community mobilization process for said provinces to encourage community#s contribution and supplying more schools by the program.
In the National Education Strategic Plan for Afghanistan where access and quality are considered the two main obstacles and challenges, distance learning is mentioned as an approach to respond to these challenges. GREAT IDEA phase I, II and III tested the distance learning methodology in Parwan province and found that it#s quite an effective medium in the Afghan scenario of lack of access and low quality education compounded with increasing insecurity.
Overall objective and approachof the project will be similar to GREAT IDEA phase III which is improving access and quality of education via distance education model with a special focus on communities# participation in expanding the program for their children. The project will specifically promote girls# enrolment in secondary (7, 8, 9) and higher secondary (10, 11, 12) educations and will reduce the drop-out rate of bothboys and girls from secondary and upper secondary educations. The Approach will build teacher#s capacities and will add satisfactory and innovative element to the learning environment. A positive indirect effect is that the increased number of secondary and high school graduates will contribute to a pool of potential teachers. The prospect of a safe and innovative secondary and higher secondary education for girls is expected to increase the transition from primary to secondary and from higher secondary to higher education through university entrance exam for girl students. Moreover, bringing (gender sensitive) innovations into the classroom is also expected to have a positive effect on the performance of teachers</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="24">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Co-ordination of Humanitarian Assistance (CHA) was founded in 1987 by a group of motivated Afghans involved in the provision of emergency relief to desperate populations in Western Afghanistan. The organisation quickly began to work on reconstruction andsustainable development. This took place in villages where hardly any developed had happened as a result of the war, and to support vulnerable groups in society, such as returning refugees.
In its twenty six years of existence CHA has implemented projects in all sectors ofrelevance to rural development: agriculture, cattle raising, basic healthcare, and water supply, rural infrastructure (irrigation, roads and public buildings). CHA has developed approaches for every segment of the population, includingwomen. Its most important tool is working with the village council Shura or Community Development council (CDC), which kicks off processes at the local level.

CHA has been involved in improvement of formal and informal education system extensively. Through it#s Galaxy training centers, CHA provided training to girls in languages, science, computer, internet and fine arts to provide growth and development opportunities for young children. It also provides training for young adults preparing them for jobmarkets. It was a partner in large education programs such as Education Quality Improvement Program EQUIP and The building education support system for teachers (BESST) to support teachers so that they are able to deliver quality education for children.

Oxfam Novib has been supporting projects since 1992. In 1998 it began to support a wider program of providing services at the regional level. Vocational and supplementary education courses have also been given in several towns. This was often to supplement the many rural programs. CHA has regularly become involved in distributing emergency relief aid. Within the organisation the importance of such relief aid is subservient to that of long-term development; it is provided to save lives.

After 2001,CHAhas grown into one of the largest and most important national NGOs in Afghanistan working in the fields of rural development, education, health and is an important implementing partners of the Ministry of Rehabilitation, Reconstruction and Development (MRRD) in its community led rural development National Solidarity Program (NSP) and in the Afghan National Development Strategy (ANDS). CHA has actively and independently engaged in and initiated innovative projects like awareness raising through the radio,targeting the marginal poor, including women, in a program focusing on the improvement of the value chain of trade in natural plants, working with Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR), the establishment of an Afghan Education Watch, and more recently it hasincorporated popular campaigning in its intervention strategies.

In 2011, Oxfam Novib launched a pilot project - an innovative distance learning model that improves quality and accessibility of education for students, especially girls, within the frameworkof the vision of the Ministry of Education. CHA was an implementing partner for Oxfam Novib. The pilot phase was completed in Feb 2013 and was able to develop a model that improved the performance of girls and boys in 21 schools in Parwan and reducedropout rate. It was also very successful in improving teachers# capacity to deliver quality education in schools.</narrative>
